{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658221","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658221"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:45:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:45:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20719"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20719","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20719"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.71,0,0.29,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13595"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95220"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13595","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13595"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20719"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78183"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11587"},{"type":"tags","id":"11762"},{"type":"tags","id":"12581"},{"type":"tags","id":"12598"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32688"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32689"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95220","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/95220"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a haematoma?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["A palpable mass of extravasated blood","A flat, non-blanching lesion smaller than 0.5 cm","A superficial collection of blood within the epidermis","A raised lesion containing serous fluid","A non-palpable discoloration caused by vasodilation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epalpable mass of extravasated blood\u003C/strong\u003E correctly describes a haematoma. When blood vessels are damaged, blood leaks into surrounding tissues. If the volume of extravasated blood is large enough, it forms a palpable mass known as a haematoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA flat, non-blanching lesion smaller than 0.5 cm\u003C/strong\u003E describes petechiae, which are pinpoint haemorrhages that occur when capillaries leak small amounts of blood into the skin.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA superficial collection of blood within the epidermis\u003C/strong\u003E describes a blood blister, which forms when blood collects between the epidermis and dermis, usually due to friction or pinching.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA non-palpable discoloration caused by vasodilation\u003C/strong\u003E describes erythema, which is redness of the skin due to increased blood flow rather than extravasation of blood.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA raised lesion containing serous fluid\u003C/strong\u003E describes a vesicle or bulla, which contains clear fluid rather than blood.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaematomas can develop from ecchymoses (bruises), which are haemorrhages of 1 to 2 cm in size, when the bleeding is substantial. Both purpura and ecchymoses can progress to haematomas and are characteristic of disorders that disrupt small blood vessels (such as vasculitis) or lead to blood vessel fragility (such as amyloidosis or scurvy).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A haematoma is a palpable mass of blood that forms when the volume of extravasated blood is large enough to create a mass.","Ecchymoses (bruises) are haemorrhages of 1 to 2 cm in size that can develop into haematomas if bleeding is substantial.","Palpable purpura and ecchymoses are characteristic of disorders that disrupt small blood vessels or lead to blood vessel fragility."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 4; page 125."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78183"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20719"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78183","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78183"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-27T18:45:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-27T18:46:51+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13595"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95220"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11587","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11587"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Haemodynamic disorders: thromboembolic disease and shock","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":3,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T15:17:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T15:17:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11762","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11762"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Bleeding and clotting","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2025-03-11T17:45:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-11T17:45:22+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12581","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12581"}